\begin{align*}
S_{ABC}&=\dfrac{1}{2}\cdot AB\cdot{h_{ABC}}\\
15&=\frac{1}{2}\cdot{3}\cdot{h_{ABC}}\\
h_{ABC}&=10\mbox{cm}
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
S_{ABD}&=\dfrac{1}{2}\cdot AB\cdot{h_{ADB}}\\
12&=\frac{1}{2}\cdot{3}\cdot{h_{ADB}}\\
h_{ADB}&=8\mbox{cm}
\end{align*}

Next, consider the right triangle formed by $CD'$ (where $D'$ is the foot of the altitude from $D$ to $AB$) and $h_{ADB}$. Since $\angle CBD'+\angle D'AB=90^\circ$ and $\angle D'AB=90^\circ-\angle CBA=60^\circ$, then $\angle CBD'=30^\circ$. Then $\tan{30^\circ}=\dfrac{CD'}{AB}=\dfrac{CD'}{3}=\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{3}}$ which gives that $CD'=\dfrac{3}{\sqrt{3}}=\sqrt{3} \mbox{cm}$. Now because $CD'-D'C=\dfrac{2h}2$ and $D'C=\dfrac{CD'}{\sqrt{3}}=\dfrac{3}{3}$ we can solve for $h$. $$\dfrac{h}{\sqrt{3}}+\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{3}}=\sqrt{3}\\
h+\dfrac{3}{\sqrt{3}}=3\\
h =\dfrac{3}{\sqrt{3}}$$

Now let's find volume:$$V_{ABCD}=\frac{1}{3} S_{ABC}h=\dfrac{1}{3}\cdot{15\cdot\sqrt{3}}=\boxed{5 \sqrt{3} \mbox{cm}^3}$$</answer>

