The implementation is pretty simple though, just try take two integers $a\leq b,$ such that $(a,2)=1,(b,3)=1,$ knowably $1\leq a\leq4,1\leq b\leq6,$ and try to figure out all possible values of $n$ generated. Writing a computer program is simple enough to brute force this. Also if maybe think: if $(a,2)=d$ and $(b,3)=e, (de,6)=e,$ so $a=\tfrac{a'}d,b=\tfrac{b'}e$ and so $ax+by=a'\lfloor \tfrac{2xd}5 \rfloor + b'\lfloor \tfrac{3ye}5 \rfloor.$ Really fairly $\tfrac{k}{de}$ should be tested for this sort of thing?


